                    <!-- FAQ Section -->
                    <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 shadow-sm dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-950" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/FAQPage">
                        <h2 class="mb-8 text-center text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-slate-900 sm:text-3xl dark:text-white">
                            Literature Review FAQs
                        </h2>

                        <div class="space-y-3">
                            <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question" class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-5 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
                                <h3 class="mb-2 text-base font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-white" itemprop="name">How many sources will be included in my literature review?</h3>
                                <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
                                    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400" itemprop="text">The number of sources depends on your academic level, topic breadth, and specific requirements. Typical ranges: undergraduate research papers (15-25 sources), Master's thesis literature reviews (30-60 sources), PhD dissertation literature reviews (50-150+ sources), and systematic reviews (50-200+ studies). We prioritize quality over quantity, focusing on relevant peer-reviewed sources that directly address your research topic. Your course requirements or institutional guidelines take precedence. We can adjust source count based on your needs and will discuss appropriate scope during consultation.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question" class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-5 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
                                <h3 class="mb-2 text-base font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-white" itemprop="name">What is the difference between a narrative and systematic literature review?</h3>
                                <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
                                    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400" itemprop="text">Narrative reviews provide comprehensive overviews of research topics with flexible search strategies, thematic organization, and interpretive synthesis. They're common in thesis/dissertation chapters and research paper introductions. Systematic reviews follow explicit, reproducible protocols with predetermined search strategies, inclusion/exclusion criteria, quality assessment tools (like PRISMA), and structured data extraction. They aim for comprehensive, unbiased evidence synthesis. Systematic reviews are more time-intensive and typically required for evidence-based practice fields (healthcare, education) or when comprehensive evidence synthesis is needed. Narrative reviews are more flexible and suitable for exploring theoretical developments or broad topic areas. We can help determine which approach is appropriate for your research needs.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question" class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-5 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
                                <h3 class="mb-2 text-base font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-white" itemprop="name">How do you identify research gaps in the literature?</h3>
                                <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
                                    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400" itemprop="text">Gap identification involves systematic analysis of existing research to determine what remains unknown or understudied. We identify: (1) topic gaps - areas where little research exists, (2) population gaps - understudied demographic groups or contexts, (3) methodological gaps - limited use of certain research methods or designs, (4) theoretical gaps - concepts needing development or testing, (5) practical gaps - knowledge-practice disconnects, and (6) geographical gaps - understudied regions or cultural contexts. We examine what researchers consistently call for in their "future research" sections, identify contradictions requiring resolution, and pinpoint questions unanswered by existing studies. Gap identification provides clear justification for your research questions and demonstrates how your work will contribute original knowledge to your field.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question" class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-5 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
                                <h3 class="mb-2 text-base font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-white" itemprop="name">Can you help with annotated bibliographies?</h3>
                                <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
                                    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400" itemprop="text">Yes! Annotated bibliographies are excellent preparatory work for full literature reviews. Each annotation includes: (1) complete citation in your required format (APA, MLA, Chicago, etc.), (2) summary of the source's main arguments, research questions, methodology, and findings, (3) evaluation of the source's credibility, strengths, limitations, and contribution to knowledge, (4) relevance statement explaining how the source relates to your research topic and questions. Annotations are typically 150-250 words per source. We organize entries alphabetically or thematically depending on your requirements. Annotated bibliographies help you systematically engage with sources before synthesizing them into comprehensive literature reviews, and many instructors assign them as preliminary assignments before thesis/dissertation proposals.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question" class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-5 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
                                <h3 class="mb-2 text-base font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-white" itemprop="name">What academic databases do you use for literature searches?</h3>
                                <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
                                    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400" itemprop="text">We conduct comprehensive searches across major academic databases appropriate for your discipline: Google Scholar (broad coverage), JSTOR (humanities and social sciences), PubMed/MEDLINE (health sciences), Web of Science (multidisciplinary), Scopus (multidisciplinary citation database), EBSCOhost databases (Academic Search Complete, Business Source Complete, PsycINFO), ProQuest Dissertations & Theses, IEEE Xplore (engineering and computer science), ScienceDirect (science and medicine), ERIC (education), HeinOnline (law), PsycINFO (psychology), CINAHL (nursing), Cochrane Library (systematic reviews), and discipline-specific repositories. We use Boolean operators, advanced search strategies, and citation chaining to ensure comprehensive coverage. Search strategies are documented transparently, especially for systematic reviews.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>

                            <div itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question" class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-5 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
                                <h3 class="mb-2 text-base font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-white" itemprop="name">How is a literature review organized?</h3>
                                <div itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
                                    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400" itemprop="text">Literature reviews can be organized thematically (most common), chronologically, methodologically, or theoretically. Thematic organization groups sources around major concepts, variables, or research themes with clear subsections and transitions. Chronological organization traces historical development of research, useful for showing theoretical evolution. Methodological organization groups studies by research methods (qualitative, quantitative, mixed methods), appropriate when comparing methodological approaches. Theoretical organization structures review around competing theories or frameworks. Most literature reviews begin with an introduction establishing topic importance and review scope, present synthesized findings organized by chosen structure, identify research gaps and inconsistencies, and conclude by linking to your research questions. We select organizational structure best suited to your topic and research goals.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

